article.description:
Nenad Krstic scored 26 points and
tapped in a missed shot by Vince Carter with 13 seconds left to
lift the New Jersey Nets over the Los Angeles Lakers 92-89 on
Friday night.
article.headline: Krstic's tip-in tops Lakers as Nets win fourth straight
article.linkText: Krstic's tip-in tops Lakers as Nets win fourth straight
article.story: EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Jason Kidd's offensive woes continued, so he turned back the clock and produced a defensive performance that belied his years. Kidd was a major reason the New Jersey Nets held Kobe Bryant to 24 points, 11 below his average, in a 92-89 win Friday night. Nenad Krstic scored 26 points and tapped in a missed shot by Vince Carter with 13 seconds left for the winning points, and Bryant missed a long 3-pointer at the buzzer. Carter, who added 24 for New Jersey, switched with Kidd on the final play and denied the Lakers star the ball until he was several feet from the 3-point line. "It was a great read by them," said Bryant. "They sent out all small, so they were able to switch everything. They took the play away from us." Up to that point, it had been Kidd who had performed yeoman's work on Bryant, who missed nine of his first 11 shots and finished 9-for-24 with seven turnovers. Kidd, meanwhile, shot 2-for-12 and saw his scoreless streak stretch to seven quarters going back to the Nets' 78-65 win over Portland Wednesday night. To compensate, he focused on pestering Bryant and getting his own teammates involved, and finished with 14 assists. "As you get older, when you pass 30, you're supposed to be too old to play defense, you're supposed to be on the downhill side," said Kidd, who turns 33 next week. "But tonight wasn't going for me offensively so I wanted to take on the assignment and just hoped he missed more than he made." It was a far cry from the teams' first meeting this season, when Kidd had 35 points and 12 assists in an overtime win at Staples Center. "We preach that regardless of where your offense is at, you have a responsibility to defend," said Nets coach Lawrence Frank. "Nobody exemplifies that more than Jason Kidd. There aren't a lot of players who can miss shots and still have a desire to go and defend." After Carter followed a miss by Richard Jefferson to give the Nets a 90-84 lead with 1:32 left, Bryant scored on a drive and then, with three players collapsing on him, found Smush Parker in the opposite corner for a 3-pointer that pulled Los Angeles within a point. But Krstic, who shot 11-for-15, was in position to grab Carter's miss and deposit it back in the basket. "We had our opportunity to make a stop and have a chance to win the ballgame, but we just couldn't make the stop," said Lakers coach Phil Jackson. "Krstic was just way too active for us all night." New Jersey (36-28) won its fourth straight game and improved to 17-3 in its last 20 home games. Lamar Odom added 18 points for the Lakers (34-33), who shot 25-for-46 (54 percent) if Bryant's totals were ignored. "All these close losses are killing us," said Luke Walton, who scored 11 points off the bench. "If we don't start winning these games, we're going to find ourselves out of the playoffs again." ^Notes:@ Lakers F Devean George (sprained right wrist) missed his sixth straight game but accompanied the team on the road trip. "It's getting better, we just can't put a date on" his return yet, Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. C Chris Mihm (ankle sprain) was also inactive ... Bryant averages between 10 and 11 free throw attempts per game, but had attempted just nine in his three most recent games, spanning 131 minutes. "I'm sure it gets noted," Jackson said before the game. "Those things tend to even out over time." He was 4-for-4 Friday ... Midway through the second quarter, Kidd threw an inbounds pass from in front of the scorer's table intended for Jefferson that went into the basket.
